description: From Middle English stert, from the verb sterten (“to start, startle”). See below.

entries.meaning: The beginning of an activity.
examples: The movie was entertaining from start to finish.

entries.meaning: A sudden involuntary movement.
The beginning point of a race, a board game, etc.
examples: Captured pieces are returned to the start of the board.

entries.meaning: An appearance in a sports game, horserace, etc., from the beginning of the event.
examples: Jones has been a substitute before, but made his first start for the team last Sunday.

entries.meaning: (horticulture) A young plant germinated in a pot to be transplanted later.
examples: You generally see nursery starts at garden centres in mid to late spring. Small annual plants are generally sold in four-packs or larger packs, with each cell holding a single young plant.

entries.meaning: An initial advantage over somebody else; a head start.
examples: to get, or have, the start

entries.meaning: (UK, slang, archaic) A happening or proceeding.
examples: “It's a rum start, old John Madingley's coming down to Tunnleton,” said Grafton, one evening in the smoking-room;  […]

description: From Middle English sterten (“to leap up suddenly, rush out”), from Old English styrtan (“to leap up, start”), from Proto-West Germanic *sturtijan (“to startle, move, set in motion”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ter- (“to be stiff”). Cognate with Old Frisian stirta (“to fall down, tumble”), Middle Dutch sterten (“to rush, fall, collapse”) (Dutch storten), Old High German sturzen (“to hurl, plunge, turn upside down”) (German stürzen), Old High German sterzan (“to be stiff, protrude”). More at stare.

entries.meaning: An instance of starting.

verbs.description: start (third-person singular simple present starts, present participle starting, simple past and past participle started)

entries.meaning: To set in motion.
examples: to start a stream of water;   to start a rumour;   to start a business

entries.meaning: To begin.
To ready the operation of a vehicle or machine.
To put or raise (a question, an objection); to put forward (a subject for discussion).
To bring onto being or into view; to originate; to invent.
examples: Sensual men agree in the pursuit of every pleasure they can start.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To begin an activity.
(intransitive) To have its origin (at), begin.
examples: The speed limit is 50 km/h, starting at the edge of town.
The blue line starts one foot away from the wall.

definitionGroups.group: To startle or be startled; to move or be moved suddenly.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To jerk suddenly in surprise.
examples: [...] The tempest's mocking elf  Points to the shipman thus the unseen shelf  He strikes on, only when the timbers start.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To awaken suddenly.
(transitive) To disturb and cause to move suddenly; to startle; to alarm; to rouse; to cause to flee or fly.
(intransitive) To flinch or draw back.
examples: Physical poison would make them start from arsenicked bread; shall not the moral poison which is in it, make them start more promptly still from slave produce?

entries.meaning: (transitive) To move suddenly from its place or position; to displace or loosen; to dislocate.
examples: to start a bone;   the storm started the bolts in the vessel

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To break away, to come loose.
(transitive, sports) To put into play.
(transitive, nautical) To pour out; to empty; to tap and begin drawing from.
(intransitive, euphemistic) To start one's periods (menstruation).

description: From Middle English stert, start (“tail, handle, projection”), from Old English steort, stert, from Proto-West Germanic *stert, from Proto-Germanic *stertaz (“tail”).  Cognate with Scots start, stairt (“side-post, shaft, upright post”), Dutch staart (“tail”), German Sterz (“tail, handle”), Swedish stjärt (“tail, arse”).

entries.meaning: A projection or protrusion; that which pokes out.
A handle, especially that of a plough.
The curved or inclined front and bottom of a water wheel bucket.
The arm, or level, of a gin, drawn around by a horse.
